Bayesian First Aid Examples

This document contains examples of all the bayes.* functions implemented in Bayesian First aid including example output from the generic functions plot, summary, diagnostics and model.code.

binom.test

A classical binomial test:

library(BayesianFirstAid)
binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.01182
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5634 0.9427
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

Prepend binom.test by bayes. to run the Bayesian “version”.

bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Bayesian First Aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.77 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.60 0.93 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.997 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.003

The idea is to respect the arguments to the original binom.test as far as possible. For example, setting p and conf.level as in…

binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.7977
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.75
## 80 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6393 0.9098
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

… is respected by bayes.binom.test:

bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Bayesian First Aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.77 
## 80% credible interval:
##   0.68 0.89 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.75 by a probability of 0.632 
## and less than 0.75 by a probability of 0.368

By assigning the result of bayes.binom.test to a variable we can get some more useful info by calling plot for looking at the posterior (and perhaps a posterior predictive check), summary for a more extensive summary than the standard print out above, and diagnostics for MCMC diagnostics. The idea is that the behavior of these functions should be consistent for all the bayes.*.test functions. 

(fit <- bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20))

## 
##  Bayesian First Aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.77 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.60 0.93 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.996 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.004

plot(fit)


summary(fit)

##   Data
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: the relative frequency of success
## x_pred: predicted number of successes in a replication
## 
##   Measures
##          mean    sd HDIlo  HDIup %<comp %>comp
## theta   0.773 0.087   0.6  0.928  0.004  0.996
## x_pred 15.473 2.506  10.0 19.000  0.000  1.000
## 
## 'HDIlo' and 'HDIup' are the limits of a 95% HDI credible interval.
## '%<comp' and '%>comp' are the probabilities of the respective parameter being
## smaller or larger than 0.5.
## 
##   Quantiles
##         q2.5%   q25% median   q75% q97.5%
## theta   0.581  0.718  0.781  0.837  0.917
## x_pred 10.000 14.000 16.000 17.000 20.000

diagnostics(fit)

## 
## Iterations = 1:5000
## Thinning interval = 1 
## Number of chains = 3 
## Sample size per chain = 5000 
## 
##   Diagnostic measures
##          mean    sd mcmc_se n_eff Rhat
## theta   0.773 0.087   0.001 14999    1
## x_pred 15.473 2.506   0.020 15000    1
## 
## mcmc_se: the estimated standard error of the MCMC approximation of the mean.
## n_eff: a crude measure of effective MCMC sample size.
## Rhat: the potential scale reduction factor (at convergence, Rhat=1).
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: The relative frequency of success
## x_pred: Predicted number of successes in a replication

Of course, in the case of bayes.binom.test the MCMC diagnostics might be a bit silly…

By asking for the model.code we get a print out of a script that runs the same analysis as bayes.binom.test. This could be copied into an R-script to study how it works or to modify it further.

model.code(fit)

## ### Model code for the Bayesian First Aid alternative to the binomial test ###
## require(rjags)
## 
## # Setting up the data
## x <- 16 
## n <- 20 
## 
## # The model string written in the JAGS language
## model_string <- "model {
##   x ~ dbinom(theta, n)
##   theta ~ dbeta(1, 1)
##   x_pred ~ dbinom(theta, n)
## }"
## 
## # Running the model
## model <- jags.model(textConnection(model_string), data = list(x = x, n = n), 
##                     n.chains = 3, n.adapt=1000)
## samples <- coda.samples(model, c("theta", "x_pred"), n.iter=5000)
## 
## # Inspecting the posterior
## plot(samples)
## summary(samples)

t.test

The alternative for the t.test is BEST.

x <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 2, sd = 5)
t.test(x)

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x
## t = 1.97, df = 29, p-value = 0.05842
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.06713  3.59610
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     1.764

bayes.t.test(x, progress.bar = "none")

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST) - one sample
## 
## data: x, n = 30
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.7 [-0.13, 3.6]
## sd of x: 5.0 [3.5, 6.5]
## 
## The mean is more than 0 by a probability of 0.965 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.035

bayes.t.test also respects the arguments of the original t.test.

y <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5)
bayes.t.test(x, y, mu = 1, conf.level = 0.5, progress.bar = "none")

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST) - two sample
## 
## data: x and y
## 
##   Estimates [50% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.7 [1.1, 2.3]
## mean of y: 11 [10, 11]
## difference of the means: -9.1 [-9.9, -8.2]
## sd of x: 5.0 [4.3, 5.3]
## sd of y: 4.2 [3.7, 4.5]
## 
## The difference of the means is more than 1 by a probability of 0 
## and less than 1 by a probability of 1

Or even…

# Creating 'paired' data
d <- data.frame(x = rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5), group = rep(c("A", "B"), 
    15))

bayes.t.test(x ~ group, paired = T, data = d, progress.bar = "none")

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST) - paired samples
## 
## data: x by group, n = 15
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean paired difference: -0.067 [-3.5, 3.4]
## sd of the paired differences: 6.3 [3.9, 9.1]
## 
## The mean difference is more than 0 by a probability of 0.48 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.52

The same generic functions (plot, summary, diagnostics) works for all fitted models from bayes.t.test.

## x_pred    1.725  5.479   0.035 25001 1.001
## 
## mcmc_se: the estimated standard error of the MCMC approximation of the mean.
## n_eff: a crude measure of effective MCMC sample size.
## Rhat: the potential scale reduction factor (at convergence, Rhat=1).
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## mu: the mean of x 
## sigma: the standard deviation of x 
## nu: the degrees-of-freedom for the t distribution fitted to x 
## eff_size: the effect size calculated as (mu - 1) / sigma
## x_pred: predicted distribution for a new datapoint generated as x


model.code(fit)

## ### Model code for Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test - one sample ###
## require(rjags)
## 
## # Setting up the data
## x <- x 
## comp_mu <-  1 
## 
## # The model string written in the JAGS language
## model_string <- "model {
##   for(i in 1:length(x)) {
##     x[i] ~ dt( mu , tau , nu )
##   }
##   x_pred ~ dt( mu , tau , nu )
##   eff_size <- (mu - comp_mu) / sigma
## 
##   mu ~ dnorm( mean_mu , precision_mu )
##   tau <- 1/pow( sigma , 2 )
##   sigma ~ dunif( sigmaLow , sigmaHigh )
##   # A trick to get an exponentially distributed prior on nu that starts at 1.
##   nu <- nuMinusOne + 1 
##   nuMinusOne ~ dexp(1/29)
## }"
## 
## # Setting parameters for the priors that in practice will result
## # in flat priors on mu and sigma.
## mean_mu = mean(x, trim=0.2)
## precision_mu = 1 / (mad(x)^2 * 1000000)
## sigmaLow = mad(x) / 1000 
## sigmaHigh = mad(x) * 1000
## 
## # Initializing parameters to sensible starting values helps the convergence
## # of the MCMC sampling. Here using robust estimates of the mean (trimmed)
## # and standard deviation (MAD).
## inits_list <- list(mu = mean(x, trim=0.2), sigma = mad(x), nuMinusOne = 4)
## 
## data_list <- list(
##   x = x,
##   comp_mu = comp_mu,
##   mean_mu = mean_mu,
##   precision_mu = precision_mu,
##   sigmaLow = sigmaLow,
##   sigmaHigh = sigmaHigh)
## 
## # The parameters to monitor.
## params <- c("mu", "sigma", "nu", "eff_size", "x_pred")
## 
## # Running the model
## model <- jags.model(textConnection(model_string), data = data_list,
##                     inits = inits_list, n.chains = 3, n.adapt=1000)
## update(model, 500) # Burning some samples to the MCMC gods....
## samples <- coda.samples(model, params, n.iter=10000)
## 
## # Inspecting the posterior
## plot(samples)
## summary(samples)

poisson.test

poisson.test(15, 3, r = 3)

## 
##  Exact Poisson test
